1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:12,871
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-harto samma-sambuddhasah Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:14,794 --> 00:00:18,399
Homage to the Buddha, fully awakened.

3
00:00:21,344 --> 00:00:27,894
So, I'm going to talk about the extraordinary ability of the Buddha to teach.

4
00:00:29,039 --> 00:00:35,588
What I'm going to talk about tonight are the extraordinary abilities that Buddha had to teach.

5
00:00:36,930 --> 00:00:44,521
So I've no doubt he was a very charismatic person, but that would not necessarily make him a good teacher.

6
00:00:45,804 --> 00:00:56,920
There was certainly no doubt that he was an extraordinarily charismatic person, but this in itself would not have made him a particularly skilled teacher.

7
00:00:57,557 --> 00:01:16,730
So he had the ability to teach large groups, monastics, nuns and so on, lay people, and adapt his teaching to them.

8
00:01:18,397 --> 00:01:28,070
And he was especially acute when talking to individuals, catching their moods and opinions, and through various techniques was able to correct their views and practices.

9
00:01:30,295 --> 00:01:38,825
He was particularly skillful, he was particularly capable when he spoke to individuals, to individuals.

10
00:01:38,846 --> 00:01:43,612
He was able to capture their moods, their opinions.

11
00:01:44,081 --> 00:01:53,355
And thanks to different techniques, he was able to correct their opinions, their points of view and also their practice.

12
00:01:55,218 --> 00:01:56,721
Now, he wasn't always successful.

13
00:01:57,302 --> 00:02:00,867
A character called Dandapani went away clicking his tongue.

14
00:02:02,930 --> 00:02:05,194
It didn't always happen.

15
00:02:05,213 --> 00:02:09,280
A certain character called Dandapani

16
00:02:09,580 --> 00:02:18,454
he walked away shaking his tongue, that is, expressing his disapproval.

17
00:02:18,813 --> 00:02:30,953
So now the usual way he discussed subjects was to first listen fully to what the other was saying, then he would repeat back to them what they had just said to make sure they both understood.

18
00:02:30,973 --> 00:02:36,701
So the way he usually dealt with

19
00:02:36,866 --> 00:03:06,520
And he would correct the person by a Socratic method of questions and answers, yeah?

20
00:03:07,056 --> 00:03:15,871
Dopodiché, correggeva la persona con un processo di domanda e risposta di tipo socratico.

21
00:03:17,272 --> 00:03:34,599
Now, once the Buddha, once he'd expressed his position, he would then restate it again clearly, and usually he would add a metaphor or an analogy, as he would say, because some people understand better that way.

22
00:03:35,389 --> 00:04:01,650
So, over the next few Buddha celebration days, I hope to take one technique after another.

23
00:04:04,312 --> 00:04:13,504
Nelle prossime giornate di celebrazioni del Buddha vorrei affrontare, trattare una tecnica dopo l'altra.

24
00:04:15,127 --> 00:04:17,430
And use a discourse to illustrate it.

25
00:04:19,613 --> 00:04:24,860
Utilizzando per illustrarla un discorso, uno dei sutta.

26
00:04:25,622 --> 00:04:29,427
So this is the shorter discourse with Malankya Putta.

27
00:04:30,942 --> 00:04:45,379
This, specifically, is the short speech with Malunkiaputta.

28
00:04:45,718 --> 00:05:00,797
This speech is an example of the way he

29
00:05:01,132 --> 00:05:30,177
Malonkia Portia was the son of Malonkia?

30
00:05:30,392 --> 00:05:33,557
who was married to an evaluator of the king of Kosala.

31
00:05:35,379 --> 00:05:43,192
Malunkhya Puta was the son of Malunkhya, who was married to a relative of the king of Kosala.

32
00:05:43,232 --> 00:05:45,636
He became a Samana, a wandering ascetic.

33
00:05:46,156 --> 00:05:53,286
When he heard the Buddha speak, he took ordination under him, but he didn't attain liberation until he was very old.

34
00:05:55,350 --> 00:05:59,016
He became a Samana, a sceptre,

35
00:05:59,266 --> 00:06:15,105
errante e quando ascoltò udì il Buddha parlare prese l'abito sott'udì con lui e però non ottenne la liberazione fino a quando non fu molto anziano.

36
00:06:16,927 --> 00:06:16,987
Ah.

37
00:06:17,007 --> 00:06:28,901
So now while Malenkiaputta was alone meditating near Savati in Jeta's grove and Atapindika's monastery, he had been considering the subjects the Buddha would not answer.

38
00:06:30,502 --> 00:06:57,875
Now these were the sort of metaphysical questions of the day.

39
00:06:58,209 --> 00:07:09,644
and he came to a decision that if the Buddha didn't give him satisfactory answers to his questions, he would lose confidence and leave the Sangha.

40
00:07:09,663 --> 00:07:20,877
It was about questions, questions that were raised, metaphysical questions of the time.

41
00:07:21,514 --> 00:07:38,059
And Malunkyaputta came to the decision that if Buddha had not given him satisfactory answers to these questions, he would have lost all faith in him and would have left the Sangha.

42
00:07:38,079 --> 00:07:44,148
So, in the late afternoon, Malunkyaputta came out of retreat and went to the Buddha.

43
00:07:44,569 --> 00:07:49,716
He bowed, sat down to one side, and told the Buddha of his thoughts.

44
00:07:50,860 --> 00:08:01,435
So, therefore, in the late afternoon, Malonkyaputta left the retreat and went back to Buddha.

45
00:08:01,454 --> 00:08:09,526
He bowed, sat down on one side, on one side, and expressed his thoughts to Buddha.

46
00:08:09,726 --> 00:08:15,718
Venerable Sir, while I was alone in meditation, the following thought arose in my mind.

47
00:08:16,319 --> 00:08:23,672
These speculative views have been left undeclared by the Blessed One, set aside and rejected by Him.

48
00:08:24,012 --> 00:08:28,680
Namely, the world is eternal or the world is not eternal.

49
00:08:29,521 --> 00:08:32,206
The world is infinite or the world is finite.

50
00:08:32,591 --> 00:08:37,797
The soul is the same as the body or is the soul one thing and the body another?

51
00:08:38,398 --> 00:08:47,245
And after the death of the Tathagata, that's the Buddha, does he exist or after death does he not exist?

52
00:08:47,826 --> 00:08:52,110
Or after death does the Tathagata both exist and not exist?

53
00:08:52,511 --> 00:08:59,038
Or after death does the Tathagata neither exist nor not exist?

54
00:09:01,533 --> 00:09:12,710
Venerable Lord, while I was meditating, the following thought came to my mind.

55
00:09:12,789 --> 00:09:19,179
These questions, these speculative questions, have been left unanswered by the Blessed One.

56
00:09:19,200 --> 00:09:22,424
They have been abandoned and rejected by Him.

57
00:09:22,445 --> 00:09:28,114
And they are the following, namely, the world is eternal or the world is not eternal.

58
00:09:28,582 --> 00:09:33,450
The world is finished or the world is infinite.

59
00:09:33,570 --> 00:09:40,278
The soul is the same thing as the body, or the soul is one thing and the body is another.

60
00:09:40,779 --> 00:09:57,763
And then again, after death, after his death, the Tathagata continues to exist, Tathagata, the transcendent Buddha, or after death a Tathagata does not exist, or again after death a Tathagata exists and does not exist,

61
00:09:58,317 --> 00:10:03,943
O ancora, dopo la morte, un tatagata non esiste né non esiste.

62
00:10:04,884 --> 00:10:12,634
Now, if the Blessed One knows, then let the Blessed One declare that to me, and I will lead the holy life under you.

63
00:10:13,976 --> 00:10:23,970
Se il Beato lo sa, allora che il Beato me lo dichiari apertamente, io condurrò la vita santa sotto la sua guida, sotto la tua guida.

64
00:10:25,029 --> 00:10:33,238
If the Blessed One does not know, then it is simple for one who does not know, does not see, to say, I do not know, I do not see.

65
00:10:33,258 --> 00:10:37,020
Then I will abandon the training and return to the lay life.

66
00:10:39,043 --> 00:10:47,770
Se il beato non sa, allora è bene che colui che non sa e non vede, dica ben chiaramente, non so, non vedo.

67
00:10:48,230 --> 00:10:52,534
In questo caso, abbandonerò l'addestramento e tornerò alla vita laica.

68
00:10:53,255 --> 00:10:53,316
Ah.

69
00:10:54,274 --> 00:11:06,105
Well now, Malanchia Putta, did I ever say to you, come Malanchia Putta, leave the holy life under me, and I will declare to you whether I have answers to these questions or not?

70
00:11:07,846 --> 00:11:08,967
No, Venerable Sir.

71
00:11:10,590 --> 00:11:23,421
Ebbene, Malanchia Putta, ti ho mai detto, vieni Malanchia Putta, conduci la vita santa sotto la mia guida, e ti dichiarerò, se ho oppure no, le risposte a queste domande,

72
00:11:24,278 --> 00:11:26,179
O Venerabile Signore.

73
00:11:26,220 --> 00:11:36,133
And did you ever say to me, Venerable Sir, I will lead the spiritual life under the Buddha only if the Buddha will declare these things to me?

74
00:11:37,193 --> 00:11:38,294
No, Venerable Sir.

75
00:11:40,238 --> 00:11:50,730
E mi hai mai detto, mi hai mai detto, Venerabile Signore, condurrò la vita spirituale sotto la guida del Buddha solo se il Buddha mi dichiarerà queste cose?

76
00:11:51,751 --> 00:11:53,374
O Venerabile Signore.

77
00:11:54,129 --> 00:12:07,481
So now the Buddha makes sure they both agree as to what has been said.

78
00:12:07,951 --> 00:12:17,863
So it seems to me that I did not say to you, Kamalankya Buddha, lead the spiritual life under me and I will declare these things to you.

79
00:12:18,462 --> 00:12:27,013
And you never said to me, sir, I will lead the spiritual life under the Buddha only if the Buddha will declare these things to me.

80
00:12:27,052 --> 00:12:32,759
In which case, you foolish man, who are you and what are you rejecting?

81
00:12:34,528 --> 00:12:46,282
So, it seems that I didn't tell you, come here, you whore, lead the spiritual life under the guidance of Buddha and I will declare these things to you.

82
00:12:46,302 --> 00:12:54,552
And you never told me, Lord, I will lead the spiritual life under the guidance of Buddha, only if Buddha will declare these things to me.

83
00:12:55,312 --> 00:13:00,097
In this case, stupid man, who are you and what are you refusing?

84
00:13:02,187 --> 00:13:17,163
Now, if anyone should say, I will not lead the holy life under the Blessed One until the Blessed One declares answers to these questions, they will still remain undeclared by the Tathagata and meanwhile the person would die.

85
00:13:17,224 --> 00:13:29,577
Ora, se qualcuno dicesse, non condurrò la vita santa sotto la guida del Buddha finché il Beato non avesse dichiarato le risposte a queste domande,

86
00:13:30,166 --> 00:13:38,277
queste rimarrebbero non dichiarate dal Tathagata e nel frattempo quella persona morirebbe.

87
00:13:39,399 --> 00:13:48,331
Now, the Buddha uses this usual technique to support what he's saying with an allegory or a metaphor.

88
00:13:49,832 --> 00:13:57,844
E adesso il Buddha usa, come al solito, una tecnica che servisse da sostegno, da supporto

89
00:13:58,128 --> 00:14:03,260
to what he was saying, thus using a metaphor or allegory.

90
00:14:04,202 --> 00:14:16,136
Suppose, Malankyaputta, a man were wounded by an arrow thickly smeared with poison, and his friends and companions, his kinsmen and relatives, brought a surgeon to treat him.

91
00:14:16,597 --> 00:14:32,876
And the man would say, I will not let the surgeon pull the arrow out until I know whether the man who wounded me was a noble, a brahmin, a merchant, or a worker, whether he was tall or short or middle height, whether the bow was long or a crossbow.

92
00:14:33,211 --> 00:14:52,591
what kind of feathers the shaft that wounded me was fitted with, whether those of a vulture, a heron, a hawk, a peacock, or a stork, and what kind of arrowhead it was that wounded me, whether it spiked, or razor-tipped, or curved, or barbed, or carved-toothed, or lancet-toothed.

93
00:14:55,114 --> 00:15:01,259
Oppone i malunchia putta che un uomo fosse ferito da una freccia densamente cosparsa di veleno,

94
00:15:01,662 --> 00:15:29,863
e che i suoi amici e compagni, parenti e congiunti, portassero un chirurgo per curarlo, e che l'uomo dicesse, non permetterò al chirurgo di estrarre questa freccia finché non saprò se l'uomo che mi ha ferito era un nobile, un bramano, un mercante o un operaio, se era alto, basso o di media statura, se l'arco era un arco lungo o una balestra.

95
00:15:30,669 --> 00:15:34,596
What kind of feather was stuck in the arrow that hurt me?

96
00:15:34,615 --> 00:15:42,988
If the feathers of a fan, or of an iron, or of a falcon, or of a peacock, or of a cicada.

97
00:15:44,068 --> 00:15:46,452
And what kind of arrow did it hurt me?

98
00:15:46,472 --> 00:15:55,446
Sharp, with a razor tip, curved, crocheted, with veal teeth, or in the shape of a spear?

99
00:15:56,977 --> 00:16:01,644
All this would still be unknown to that man, and meanwhile he would die.

100
00:16:01,705 --> 00:16:17,366
So too, Malankyaputta, if anyone should say, I will not lead the holy life under the Blessed One until the Blessed One declares on these questions, they would still remain undeclared by the Tathagata, and meanwhile that person would die.

101
00:16:19,708 --> 00:16:26,500
All this would still not remain known to that man and in the meantime he would die.

102
00:16:26,519 --> 00:16:43,489
In the same way, Malunchia Putta, if someone said, I will not lead the holy life under the blessed until the blessed is pronounced on such matters, well, these would remain undeclared by Altatagata and in the meantime that person would die.

103
00:16:43,890 --> 00:16:54,302
Now the Buddha goes on to say that it's not true that the spiritual life cannot be led unless these speculative views are answered, and he reaffirms his position.

104
00:16:55,884 --> 00:17:10,422
Poi il Buddha prosegue affermando che non è vero che la vita spirituale non possa essere condotta senza che tali questioni speculative trovino risposta, e riafferma la sua posizione.

105
00:17:11,836 --> 00:17:23,808
Whether such views are answered or not, there is still birth, there is still ageing, there is still death, there is still sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief and despair.

106
00:17:24,770 --> 00:17:30,297
And it is the destruction of these, right here and now, that I prescribe for.

107
00:17:31,999 --> 00:17:41,269
Se tali questioni trovino risposto meno, c'è sempre nascita, c'è sempre invecchiamento, c'è sempre morte.

108
00:17:41,856 --> 00:17:48,807
Ci sono sempre dolore, lamento, tristezza, afflizione e disperazione.

109
00:17:49,387 --> 00:17:54,375
Ed è la distruzione di queste cose, proprio qui e ora, che io prescrivo.

110
00:17:55,477 --> 00:18:04,911
Therefore, malunque putta, remember what I have left undeclared as undeclared, and remember what I have declared as declared.

111
00:18:06,173 --> 00:18:20,287
And why have I left them undeclared?

112
00:18:20,507 --> 00:18:22,028
Because they are not beneficial.

113
00:18:22,469 --> 00:18:26,073
They do not belong to the fundamentals of the spiritual life.

114
00:18:26,093 --> 00:18:34,340
They do not lead to disenchantment, to dispassion, to cessation, to peace, to direct knowledge, to awakening, to nibbana.

115
00:18:34,944 --> 00:18:37,387
That is why I have left them undeclared.

116
00:18:37,407 --> 00:18:41,311
E perché li ho lasciati non dichiarati?

117
00:18:41,913 --> 00:18:59,394
Perché non sono benefici, non appartengono ai fondamenti della vita santa e spirituale, non conducono al disincanto, al distacco, alla cessazione, alla pace, alla conoscenza diretta, al risveglio, al nibbana.

118
00:18:59,413 --> 00:19:02,176
Ecco perché li ho lasciati non dichiarati.

119
00:19:03,218 --> 00:19:04,799
And what have I declared?

120
00:19:05,134 --> 00:19:07,698
There is suffering and unsatisfactoriness.

121
00:19:07,979 --> 00:19:11,423
There is the origin of suffering and unsatisfactoriness.

122
00:19:11,443 --> 00:19:22,898
There is a cessation of suffering and unsatisfactoriness and there is a way leading to the cessation of suffering and unsatisfactoriness.

123
00:19:22,919 --> 00:19:24,421
And what did I declare?

124
00:19:25,142 --> 00:19:27,945
There is suffering and dissatisfaction.

125
00:19:28,547 --> 00:19:32,491
There is the origin of suffering and dissatisfaction.

126
00:19:33,011 --> 00:19:43,871
C'è la cessazione della sofferenza e dell'insoddisfazione e c'è la via che conduce alla cessazione della sofferenza e dell'insoddisfazione.

127
00:19:45,013 --> 00:19:53,788
That is what the Blessed One said, and the Venerable Malamkhya Buddha was satisfied and delighted in the Blessed One's words.

128
00:19:55,010 --> 00:19:56,994
Questo è ciò che disse il Beato.

129
00:19:57,295 --> 00:20:03,481
The venerable Manu Khyaputta was satisfied and delighted by the words of the Blessed One.

130
00:20:04,563 --> 00:20:13,913
So this discourse shows us how the Buddha generally taught by first listening and then probing and then finally stating his teachings and his use of metaphor.

131
00:20:15,595 --> 00:20:24,585
This discourse shows how in general the Buddha taught first by listening, then

132
00:20:24,817 --> 00:20:31,690
and then finally affirming his teaching, and finally the use of the metaphor.

133
00:20:32,811 --> 00:20:47,636
And he would not be drawn into hypothetical, metaphysical or speculative discussions.

134
00:20:48,680 --> 00:21:03,402
They were simply not conducive to the spiritual aim of liberating oneself from dukkha, suffering and unsatisfactoriness.

135
00:21:03,642 --> 00:21:13,057
The Buddha tells us there is a limit beyond reason.

136
00:21:14,459 --> 00:21:16,662
Reason and logic simply cannot go.

137
00:21:17,012 --> 00:21:23,501
and which can only be transcended and realized by direct experience.

138
00:21:23,622 --> 00:21:43,611
And finally, the reason he refused to answer questions about himself

139
00:21:44,079 --> 00:21:59,442
What happened to him after he died was that these questions invariably arose from some idea of a self that would either exist or not exist, exist and not exist, and neither exist nor not exist.

140
00:22:01,164 --> 00:22:12,602
And finally, the reason why he refused to answer these questions about himself, the Tathagata, that is, what would have happened after his death,

141
00:22:13,190 --> 00:22:15,612
Very good.

142
00:22:17,894 --> 00:22:41,037
I hope this little talk has been of some assistance, that it has not caused confusion.

143
00:22:43,160 --> 00:22:49,470
Spero che questo piccolo sermone sia stato di aiuto e che non abbia creato confusione alcuna.

144
00:22:49,911 --> 00:22:58,443
That by your careful practice and reading you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

145
00:22:59,546 --> 00:23:09,442
E che grazie alla vostra pratica, alla lettura dei discorsi sarete liberati dalla sofferenza sperabilmente prima piuttosto che dopo.

146
00:23:10,083 --> 00:23:10,163
Ah.

